result.execSummary:
The defendant Markus A. Hernandez was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Markus A. Hernandez appeared by video, Attorney Mark Walter Frank appeared in court for Markus A. Hernandez, Attorney Lisa A. Riniker appeared in court for State of Wisconsin. Waiver of preliminary hearing reviewed and signed on February 22, 2022. Defendant heard and does not wish to waive preliminary hearing now. Attorney Frank heard. Courtroom cleared for defendant to speak with counsel. Court resumes. Attorney Frank heard and now questions competency. Competency was not in question at time of review of waiver. Court heard and finds defendant freely and knowingly waived right to preliminary hearing. Court finds probable cause to bind over for trial. Court orders competency exam. Defendant is residing in motel in Green Bay, Wisconsin. Mail to be sent to his mother. Victim appeared by zoom at end of hearing. Court summarizes status of case. Victim requests no contact provision be lifted. Court heard and enters order deleting no contact provision. New bond to be sent to defendant for signature. Court sets status as to competency.
